                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d315">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">862.51 Bondholders/216: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dodd</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-11-28T10:00:00+01:00"
                            >November 28, 1934—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received November 28—9:05 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>223. No answer so far to your 131, November 21, 2 p.m., but official news agency
                    after giving very brief summary of American note observes that real point at
                    issue is not that raised but practical question of transfer. Only way to obtain
                    enough foreign exchange is to increase exports: all efforts German Government to
                    enter into negotiations to this end unavailable: Germany is not the only debtor
                    country unable to pay the United States.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Dodd</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
